    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-02-21T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-02-21T22:00:00-05:00" n="133"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d133">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/14335: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-02-22T10:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 22, 1939—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 22—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>127. Reference Embassy’s No. 96, February 11, 6 p.m.<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d133fn23">Not printed.</note> and other telegrams on the same
                    subject.</p>
                <p>The third session of the People’s Political Council adjourned February 21 after
                    what is reported to have been the most harmonious session yet held. A digest of
                    Chiang Kai Shek’s closing address will be telegraphed later.<note n="23a"
                        xml:id="d133fn23a">Telegram No. 135, February 25, 10 a.m., from the Chargé
                        in China, not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>According to information from a reliable source, perhaps the most significant
                    conclusion to be drawn from the meetings is that an overwhelming decision was
                    reached to realize the object of establishing a democratic form of government in
                    China and conversely to reject the proposals of a small minority for the
                    creation of a totalitarian regime. It is not unlikely that the Generalissimo
                    played a major part in bringing about this decision.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
